</dd>

  <hr /><a name="departmentalemblem"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DEPARTMENTAL EMBLEM</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#emblemmg">emblem military and governmental/departmental</a>&rsquo; under &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#emblem">emblem</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2328.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2328.gif" alt="depth" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Emblem of <a href="gb_brail.html#old">British Railways 1949-1965</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  <hr /><a name="departmentalflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DEPARTMENTAL (or DEPARTMENT) FLAG</dt>
  <dd>1) The phrases used to describe the flag of a sub-national entity when that entity is 
  called a �department� � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#subnationalflag">sub-national flag</a>&rsquo;.<br>
  2) These phrases can also represent the flag of administrative or clerical agencies within a 
  governmental structure.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4720.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4720.gif" alt="departmental flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4721.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4721.gif" alt="departmental flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4722.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4722.gif" alt="departmental flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="fr-84.html">Vaucluse</a>, France (fotw); 
  <a href="tw^gpd.html">General Political Warfare Department</a> 1958 1986, Taiwan (fotw); 
  <a href="ph_gov.html#dbm">Department of Budget and Management</a>, The Philippines (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="depth"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DEPTH</dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvw2.html#width">width 1)</a>&rsquo;.
  <dd>2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvw2.html#width">width 3)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1135.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1135.gif" alt="depth" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3431.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3431.gif" alt="depth" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Example of 1); Flag of <a href="hr-ri-bs.html">Ba�ka</a>, Croatia (fotw)</em>
  
  <hr /><a name="descate"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DESCATE </dt>
  <dd>(adj) A term used to describe a rounded (or lanceolate) fly into which a &lsquo;V&rsquo; shaped notch 
  has been cut, and a shape often seen in UK cavalry guidons &ndash; cloven descate or 
  rounded swallowtail (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf5.html#fly">fly 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg6.html#guidon">guidon 2</a>)&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh6.html#hussarcut">hussar cut</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#lanceolate">lanceolate</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail">swallow tail(ed)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1189.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1189.gif" alt="[descate flag]" border="0" width="162" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2118.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2118.gif" alt="[descate flag]" border="0" width="162" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>Guidon of the <a href="gb~mepo.html#guidon">Metropolitan Police Mounted Branch</a>, UK (fotw); Guidon of the Blues and Royals, UK (Graham Bartram/&#381;eljko Heimer)</em>
  <p><em>Please note that in UK usage this pattern of flag/pennant is a direct development of the shape formerly carried by formations of cavalry
  - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvch.html#chamferedswallowtail">chamfered swallow-tail</a>&rsquo;.</em>
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2119.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2119.gif" alt="[descate flag]" border="0" width="162" height="108"></a>
  <br><em>Guidon of the <a href="gb^glo2.html#stdd1797">Royal Gloucestershire Yeomanry 1797</a>, UK (fotw)  </em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="descendingdiag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DESCENDING DIAGONAL </dt>
  <dd>1) The term for a diagonal stripe that runs from the upper hoist to the 
  lower fly, and is centred on the corners of the flag &ndash; a bend, falling 
  diagonal, hoist-diagonal, right diagonal or right diagonal bar  - but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#bend">bend</a>&rsquo; and 
  <a href="vxt!dv-9.html">Appendix IX</a> (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva8.html#ascendingdiag">ascending diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#eastsouth">east-south diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#ewdiagonal">east-west diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#northeast">north-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#northsouth">north-south diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#southeast">south-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#southnorth">south-north diagonal</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westeast">west-east diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westnorth">west-north diagonal</a>&rsquo;,
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#westsouth">west-south diagonal</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>2) The term may also be used to describe the division line on a bicolour 
  divided diagonally per bend as shown below &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp3.html#perbend">per bend 1)</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#beicolor">bicolour 1)</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4723.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4723.gif" alt="descending diagonal" border="0"  height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4724.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4724.gif" alt="descending diagonal" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d111a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d111a.gif" alt="descending diagonal" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="nl-ut-ut.html">Utrecht</a>, The Netherlands (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="mt-40.html">L-Imqabba</a>, Malta (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="cz-bk-rs.html">Ra&scaron;ov</a>, Czechia (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  <hr /><a name="desecrate"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DESECRATE </dt>
  <dd>1) (v) To maliciously damage or mistreat a flag for political or other motives, or to use a flag in a way that is 
  considered disrespectful or inappropriate (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr6.html#rulesofrespect">rules of respect</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt!dv-2.html">Appendix II</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd3.html#disfigure">disfigure</a>&rsquo;.  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="designationflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DESIGNATING (OF HEADQUARTERS) FLAG</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#hqflag">headquarters flag 2)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1376.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1376.gif" alt="designating headquarters flag" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Designating/Headquarters Flag of a <a href="us^ar1s.html">Brigadier General</a>, US Army (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="deskflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DESK FLAG (or DESK TOP FLAG) </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-t.html#tableflag">table flag</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1341.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1341.gif" alt="desk flag" border="0" width="90" height="221" /></a><br />
  <em>Desk/Table Flag of <a href="hr-pn-gc.html">Graci�ce</a>, Croatia (fotw and CS)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="destinationflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DESTINATION FLAG </dt>
  <dd>The term describing a custom whereby the flag of the country of destination 
  may be flown at the fore by a merchant ship or pleasure vessel 
  when about to sail (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf6.html#fore">fore</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <hr /><a name="device"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DEVICE </dt>
  <dd>1) Originally a heraldic term for a temporary mark extra to the coat of arms 
  to distinguish those who entered the lists at tournaments, it now refers specifically 
  to the &lsquo;motto (see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm4.html#motto">motto</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>2) The term used to describe those marks of difference that appear on English military 
  colours of the 17th Century (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#stand">stand 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-v.html#venn">venn</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>3) A term sometimes inaccurately applied to any charge, badge or emblem &ndash; 
  see �<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#badge">badge</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvch.html#charge">charge</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#emblem">emblem</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2329a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d2329a.gif" alt="device example" border="0" height="108" /></a>  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2329b.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d2329b.gif" alt="device example" border="0" height="108" /></a>  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2329c.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d2329c.gif" alt="device example" border="0" height="108" /></a>  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2329d.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d2329d.gif" alt="device example" border="0" height="108" /></a><br>
  <em>Major&rsquo;s then First, Second and Third Captain&rsquo;s Colours, 
  <a href="gb^ltb3.html">Westminster Liberty Regiment</a>, London. England c1641 (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="dexter"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DEXTER </dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for the right hand side of a flag or shield from the point 
  of view of the bearer, or the left hand side from the point of view of an observer 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sinister">sinister</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>  
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1417.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d1417.gif" alt="dexter example" border="0" height="108" /></a>

<hr /><a name="dexteredge"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DEXTER EDGE</dt>
  <dd>1) With regard to a shield see &lsquo;<a href="#dexter">dexter</a>&rsquo; above.</dd>
  <dd>2) A term that may be used in describing the left hand facing edge of a banner or 
  gonfalon which is hung from a crossbar, and equivalent to the top edge of a conventionally 
  hoisted flag &ndash; the leading edge (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html">banner 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gonfalon">gonfalon</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d781.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d781.gif" alt="dexter edge example" border="0" width="92" height="263" /></a></p>

  <hr /><a name="dexterhoist"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DEXTER HOIST  (HOISTED or HOISTING)</dt>
  <dd>Rarely employed terms, but those that may be used when the obverse of a flag is depicted (or is 
  manufactured) with its hoist to the observer&rsquo;s left in accordance with Western tradition &ndash; 
  left hoisted - see 
  &lsquo;<a href="#dexter">dexter</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sinisterhoist">sinister hoist</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh4.html#hoist">hoist 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#obverse">obverse</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reverse">reverse</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d1006.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1006.gif" alt="dexter hoist" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>National Flag of </em> <a href="md.html"><em>Moldova</em></a><em> (fotw)</em>
  <p>
  <em>Please note, it is usually felt unnecessary to specify the dexter hoist since it is a default assumption 
  in most cases.</em>
</dl>
